result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Landan William Swenson

records.addlTxt:
2:24 PM Defendant Landan William Swenson in court.  Attorney Nathan M Cockerham in court for Landan William Swenson.  Attorney Angela M Wilson in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls case. State indicates will plead guilty to counts 1, 2, and 3 in 22CF61 and DRI on 22CF218. Asks for a deferred agreement as to count 1, and for counts 2 and 3, sentence withheld for 3 years probation, with conditions of DOC programming, $100 fine on each count plus costs, concurrent, no contact with Victim. Attorney Cockerham indicates will be a no contest plea. 
Court recounts charges and possible penalties. Defendant pleads no contest. Court informs defendant of rights given up by their plea. Attorney stipulates to a factual basis. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been freely, voluntarily and intelligently made. Court finds Defendant understands all the rights they are waiving by their plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is deferred on Count 1 and entered on Counts 2 and 3. Everything else dismissed but read it. DA will monitor agreement.
State makes statements regarding sentencing. Asking court not to order expungement due to nature of the case. Society will be harmed if expunged, needs to be kept on his record. Victim still suffering. Points out inconsistencies in evaluation. 
Attorney Cockerham argues for expungement. Argues special disposition statute. Participated in evaluation on a voluntary basis, it was not mandatory for this agreement. Asking for expungement upon completion, will and already has had consequences from this matter. 
State and defense agree to no sex offender registry.  Defendant makes statements. 

Court orders sentence withheld on Counts 2 and 3, for 3 years probation, conditions to include $100 fine plus costs on each count, DOC programming, no contact with Victim.

Court makes statements regarding expungement. Society must be protected. Court not 100% convinced that society will not be harmed. Court does not approve expungement. 

Bail to be converted to 5000 signature bond.
Plea/sentencing hearing on August 9, 2022 at 02:30 pm.

3:16 PM Prosecuting attorney Angela M Wilson in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Landan William Swenson in court.  Attorney Nathan M Cockerham in court for Landan William Swenson. Defendant verifies an address for the defendant. Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the complaint, waives a formal reading, and requests a preliminary hearing. Asks for $500 signature bond with special conditions of no intentional contact with minors. Attorney Cockerham does not object to signature bond. Notes that defendant voluntarily appears and has made all other court appearances. Attorney Cockerham asks the court to consider an exception to the no contact to allow him to work with minors. Given the defendant's age, he has not been able to find employment where there are not minors that are employed there. State notes that the defendant has been in good contact with his attorney and shows up voluntarily today for court. State notes that contact with minors while supervised could be addressed in the future. There could be a stipulation when the defendant finds employment and feels signature bond is appropriate. Court notes concerns over underlying charges and ability to follow court orders. Court orders $5,000 signature bond. No intentional contact with minors. Court notes that motions may be made when defendant has employment to address possible work exception.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for June 22, 2022 at 08:30 am.
